Aluminum foil is able to relieve aches and pains in the bones and joints, as well as in the back of the neck and arms.  Wrap the affected area in aluminum foil and secure it with a bandage. Aluminum foil is frequently found on the kitchen table. It is useful for keeping food moist when wrapped. Although some people believe that cooking with aluminum foil is dangerous because the substance can cause harm when enters the food, others believe that this thin paper is safe to use alongside food.

Aluminum is a naturally occurring mineral found in almost everything we consume, from vegetables to fruits to water. Aluminum can even be found in foods that have undergone certain preservation and packaging processes.

Hence, even if aluminum foil is exposed, it is not a problem as long as it is in a very tolerable amount in the body.
Aluminum foil is still used today due to various studies that support the above.

Wrap the legs in 4 to 5 sheets of aluminum foil. Use cheesecloth or tissue paper to wrap the insert sheet.  Remove it after an hour and repeat every two hours. When you get the flu three times in a row, it usually goes away.

In cases of minor burns, aluminum foil can also be used as first aid. 
After cleaning the wound, wrap it in gauze and cover it with aluminum foil. 
This paper can relieve existing aches and pains while also preventing further skin inflammation.

Place a few sheets of aluminum foil in the freezer for exhaustion. Spread it out and place it over your face to refresh it once it has cooled and frozen.  Aluminum foil can also be used to relieve eye bag irritation. Cut a small sheet of freezer-stored paper and place it over your eyes for a few minutes.

Wrap your leg in aluminum foil to relieve muscle fatigue. Allow to stand for a few moments to relieve fatigue. These treatments are only effective for minor health issues. You should still seek medical attention for more serious disorders or illnesses.
